---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const description =
  "Plain Theory Labs — certification framework for sustainable AI compute infrastructure";
---

<BaseLayout title="Plain Theory Labs — certification framework for sustainable AI compute infrastructure" description={description}>

  <!-- Section 1 — Hero (dark) -->
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-inner">
      <span class="hero-tag">AI Compute Certification</span>
      <h1>The infrastructure behind AI is mostly invisible. We are making it legible.</h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">
        Plain Theory Labs measures what GPU clusters are actually
        doing, scores it against a documented methodology, and
        delivers findings that research computing directors can
        act on and sustainability offices can report against.
      </p>
      <p class="hero-sub">
        We are AI and HPC systems engineers. We have spent our careers
        inside these systems — configuring schedulers at research
        universities, tuning GPU allocations at academic medical
        centers, reading the telemetry that most organizations
        collect and never fully use. We know what efficient
        infrastructure looks like. We built PTL because no
        independent standard existed to say so.
      </p>
      <a href="mailto:jesus@plaintheory.org" class="cta-link-light">Start a pilot</a>
    </div>

    <!-- Score strip immediately below hero text -->
    <div class="score-strip">
      <div class="score-strip-inner">
        <div class="score-item">
          <span class="score-value frontier">0.873</span>
          <span class="score-meta">FRONTIER<br/>NERSC Perlmutter</span>
        </div>
        <div class="score-item">
          <span class="score-value optimized">0.814</span>
          <span class="score-meta">OPTIMIZED<br/>Meridian AI</span>
        </div>
        <div class="score-item">
          <span class="score-value optimized">0.736</span>
          <span class="score-meta">OPTIMIZED<br/>OLCF Frontier</span>
        </div>
        <div class="score-item">
          <span class="score-value developing">0.450</span>
          <span class="score-meta">DEVELOPING<br/>MIT Supercloud</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 2 — What actually happens (warm prose) -->
  <section class="prose-section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-label">What actually happens when you use AI</span>
      <p>
        Every query sent to a large language model triggers a
        cascade of physical events most people never consider.
        A GPU wakes up and draws between 300 and 700 watts.
        A cooling system compensates for the heat. A power
        infrastructure conditions electricity from the grid.
      </p>
      <p>
        A single A100 running continuously for a year consumes
        roughly <span class="datum">3,500 kWh</span>. A modest research cluster of 100
        GPUs draws more power than a small neighborhood. The
        largest training runs now require facilities measured
        in hundreds of megawatts.
      </p>
      <p>
        This infrastructure exists. It is operating today.
        Its footprint is growing faster than anyone is
        measuring it rigorously.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 3 — The measurement problem (warm prose) -->
  <section class="prose-section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-label">The data exists. The grades don't.</span>
      <p>
        HPC centers run Prometheus, Grafana, DCGM, and Slurm
        accounting. They collect utilization rates, job
        runtimes, power draw, and queue statistics around
        the clock. The data has always been there.
      </p>
      <p>
        What does not exist is a methodology that turns that
        data into a grade. A score that tells an organization
        not just what is happening, but how it compares to
        what is achievable — and what a specific change
        would produce.
      </p>
      <p>
        Without that, monitoring data has no policy weight.
        An HPC director cannot write a procurement requirement
        around a utilization rate with no reference point.
        A sustainability office cannot report against a number
        with no standard. A funding agency cannot evaluate
        an efficiency claim with no independent basis.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 4 — Engine table (dark) -->
  <section class="dark-section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-label-dark">The certification framework</span>
      <p style="font-family: var(--serif); font-size: 1rem; color: var(--on-dark-4); line-height: 1.65; max-width: 560px; margin-bottom: 32px;">
        Nine components. PROFILE characterizes the cluster before
        analysis begins. Five engines grade specific dimensions of
        infrastructure operations. GRADE scores the findings into
        a PTL Score and certification tier. ATLAS converts the
        certification into a ranked action plan. CLAW automates
        continuous data collection from inside the cluster environment.
      </p>
      <div class="engine-table">
        <div class="engine-row">
          <span class="engine-name">PROFILE</span>
          <span class="engine-desc">Cluster characterization · scheduler detection · engine routing</span>
        </div>
        <div class="engine-row">
          <span class="engine-name">ACE</span>
          <span class="engine-desc">GPU utilization · job efficiency · right-sizing</span>
        </div>
        <div class="engine-row">
          <span class="engine-name">COOL</span>
          <span class="engine-desc">PUE efficiency · cooling system performance</span>
        </div>
        <div class="engine-row">
          <span class="engine-name">FLUX</span>
          <span class="engine-desc">Carbon accounting methodology · greenwashing detection</span>
        </div>
        <div class="engine-row">
          <span class="engine-name">PACE</span>
          <span class="engine-desc">Scheduler policy · over-requesting patterns</span>
        </div>
        <div class="engine-row">
          <span class="engine-name">CORE</span>
          <span class="engine-desc">Hardware-workload fit · fleet age · embodied carbon</span>
        </div>
        <div class="engine-row">
          <span class="engine-name">GRADE</span>
          <span class="engine-desc">PTL Score 0.0–1.0 · tier: DEVELOPING through FRONTIER</span>
        </div>
        <div class="engine-row">
          <span class="engine-name">ATLAS</span>
          <span class="engine-desc">Ranked recommendations · trajectory projection</span>
        </div>
        <div class="engine-row">
          <span class="engine-name claw">CLAW</span>
          <span class="engine-desc">NemoClaw intake agent · continuous telemetry · self-describing clusters</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 5 — Certification tiers (warm) -->
  <section class="prose-section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-label">Certification tiers</span>
      <p style="max-width: 560px; margin-bottom: 28px;">
        PTL scores clusters on a 0.0 to 1.0 scale.
        The performance tier is shorthand for where the score lands.
        The number is the truth — the tier is the label.
      </p>
      <div class="tier-table">
        <div class="tier-row">
          <span class="tier-name">FRONTIER</span>
          <span class="tier-desc">All five engines · composite ≥ 0.85</span>
        </div>
        <div class="tier-row">
          <span class="tier-name">OPTIMIZED</span>
          <span class="tier-desc">Four or more engines · composite ≥ 0.70</span>
        </div>
        <div class="tier-row">
          <span class="tier-name">CAPABLE</span>
          <span class="tier-desc">Three or more engines · composite ≥ 0.60</span>
        </div>
        <div class="tier-row">
          <span class="tier-name">DEVELOPING</span>
          <span class="tier-desc">Two or more engines · composite ≥ 0.45</span>
        </div>
        <div class="tier-row">
          <span class="tier-name">BASELINE</span>
          <span class="tier-desc">ACE only — first measurement, starting point</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p style="margin-top: 28px; max-width: 560px; font-size: 1rem; color: #666;">
        The first system we assessed was MIT Supercloud, on a
        peer-reviewed public dataset of 73,367 production jobs.
        PTL Score 0.450. Tier: DEVELOPING. The top recommendation
        from ATLAS was specific enough to act on the same week.
      </p>
      <a href="/certification" class="cta-link" style="margin-top: 24px;">
        How certification works →
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 6 — Built on real data (warm) -->
  <section class="prose-section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-label">Built on real data</span>
      <p>
        The Adaptive Compute Efficiency Engine is the first of
        five analytical engines in the stack. It ingests Slurm
        scheduler exports, scores every job against a documented
        efficiency methodology, and produces findings with
        confidence labels and fully disclosed assumptions.
      </p>
      <p>
        We validated it on a published, peer-reviewed dataset
        from a production system. The numbers below are not
        projections.
      </p>
      <div class="findings">
        <p>MIT Supercloud HPCA22 dataset — 73,367 production jobs</p>
        <p><strong>25.7%</strong> average GPU utilization</p>
        <p><strong>$255,271</strong> in recoverable savings identified</p>
        <p>DEVELOPING tier — PTL Score 0.450</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 7 — AI infrastructure is a performance problem (warm) -->
  <section class="prose-section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-label">AI infrastructure is a performance problem</span>
      <p>
        GPU clusters operate at a fraction of their theoretical capacity.
        Scheduler configuration, resource allocation, cooling setpoints,
        and hardware-workload fit all determine how much useful work a
        cluster actually produces per watt of power consumed.
      </p>
      <p>
        PTL measures that gap. The score reflects how close a cluster is
        to the frontier of what its hardware can do — not against an
        abstract ideal, but against documented benchmarks for the specific
        equipment and workload type in use.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 8 — Efficiency is a scientific priority (warm) -->
  <section class="prose-section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-label">Efficiency is a scientific priority</span>
      <p>
        AI is central to how science gets done today. Drug
        discovery, climate modeling, genomics, and fusion
        research all depend on GPU clusters operating at scale.
      </p>
      <p>
        A cluster running at <span class="datum">15% average GPU utilization</span> is not
        just wasting energy. It is wasting research capacity.
        The most ambitious science should run on the most
        efficiently operated infrastructure. Those two things
        are not in tension.
      </p>
      <p>
        The data to understand this already exists inside
        every HPC center. We provide the methodology to
        make it legible.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 9 — Pilot (dark, closing) -->
  <section class="pilot-section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-label-dark">Start a pilot</span>
      <p>
        We are taking three pilot organizations this quarter.
        You provide cluster access or a data export. CLAW can
        collect everything automatically from inside your
        OpenShell environment, or we walk through a manual
        export together. Either way, under two hours of your time.
      </p>
      <p>The findings are yours. We keep the methodology.</p>
      <a href="mailto:jesus@plaintheory.org" class="cta-link-light" style="margin-top: 32px;">
        jesus@plaintheory.org
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

</BaseLayout>
